**C3scan.io Web Apps Design Specification (v0.2.2)**  
**Admin Tool \+ Customer Tool**

Build-ready functional specification based on PilotoMail UI screenshots (Thinkspace tenant)

Last updated: 2026-02-09

# **One-page Summary**

* Purpose: Replace PilotoMail with C3scan.io Admin Tool (mailroom \+ operator admin) and Customer Tool (mailbox customers) while preserving proven workflows.  
* MVP must support: Mail intake \+ assignment, Customer action requests (Forward, Open & Scan), Request fulfillment in Admin (attachments, notes, activity trail), Mailbox \+ member management (mailbox managers \+ authorized members), Compliance (USPS 1583 workflow), and secure image/document handling.  
* Key objects: operator, location, company, mailbox, member (portal user), authorized member (USPS roster), mail\_item, request, request\_attachment, request\_note, request\_event; all scoped by location with strict tenant isolation.  
* Critical flows: (1) Admin uploads mail \-\> assigns mailbox; (2) Customer submits request (Forward/Open & Scan) \-\> Admin fulfills \-\> Customer sees completion \+ downloads; (3) Compliance assistant \-\> admin review/override \-\> exports.  
* Integrations (v0.2): Stripe (billing/identity optional), EasyPost (labels), OfficeRnD/Deskworks (tenant mapping \+ billing optional).  
* Security: Storage paths only (no public URLs), signed URLs for viewing/download, RLS/role checks server-side, and append-only audit events for request lifecycle \+ settings changes.  
* Acceptance gates: Forward request completion stores label/tracking (if enabled) and logs events; Open & Scan requires at least one deliverable attachment before completion; customer can download attachments after completion.

# **1\. Purpose and scope**

This document specifies the v0.2 scope for two web applications that replace PilotoMail:

* C3scan Admin Tool: internal operator dashboard for mail intake, mailbox management, compliance, requests, billing, and settings.  
* C3scan Customer Tool: mailbox manager portal for viewing mail and issuing actions (open and scan, forward, pickup, shred, recycle, deposit, leave at office) plus USPS compliance workflow (Form 1583).

The PilotoMail screenshots are treated as the UI contract. Any behavior not explicitly shown is specified here to make the system implementable and testable.

## **1.1 Goals**

* Achieve functional parity with the PilotoMail flows shown in screenshots for a single operator with multiple locations.  
* Support a secure multi-tenant model: operator \-\> location \-\> mailbox, with role-based access for staff and customers.  
* Enable mail intake from the C3scan iOS app (envelope scan) and from manual upload in the Admin Tool.  
* Provide a compliance assistant workflow that collects identity and address proof, generates USPS Form 1583, and records signing and approval.

## **1.2 Non-goals (v0.2)**

* Building a full end-user billing portal (beyond viewing payment methods and invoices).  
* Advanced analytics, custom reporting, or a full audit log UI (logging is required, UI can come later).  
* International mail compliance requirements (v0.2 targets US USPS Form 1583).  
* Replacing every PilotoMail integration; only the integrations shown in screenshots are in-scope.

## **1.3 Definitions**

| Term | Meaning |
| :---- | :---- |
| Operator | A coworking company that operates one or many Locations (e.g., Thinkspace with Seattle and Redmond; 25N; Blankspaces). |
| Location | A physical site operated by an Operator that receives and processes mail. |
| Member | A customer person tied to a mailbox for operational or compliance reasons (may or may not have portal access). Members can own one or many Companies. |
| Company | A business or entity that receives mail and can have one or many Mailboxes. A Company can have one or many Authorized Members (employees) for USPS compliance. |
| Mailbox | A mailbox with a PMB number and a mailbox name, typically associated to a Company and serviced at a Location. |
| Mailbox Manager | The portal user who can act in the Customer Tool for a mailbox. This is always the Member who signed the lease. A Mailbox Manager can also be an Authorized Member. |
| Authorized Member | A Member included in the USPS compliance roster for a Company or Mailbox, even if they are not a portal user. In v0.2, Authorized Members are stored in `company_alias` where `alias_type = "authorized_member"` and `alias_name` is the person’s full legal name. | (full legal name exactly as on government ID)
| Mail item | An incoming piece of mail or package represented by images and metadata. |
| Request | An action requested by a customer for a mail item (Open and Scan, Forward Mail, Pickup, etc.). |
| Compliance case | The set of identity and address documents and Form 1583 signing required for USPS compliance. |

### **1.3.1 Relationship model (at a glance)**

* Operator → has many Locations
* Operator → serves many Members
* Member → can own many Companies
* Company → can have many Mailboxes
* Company → can have many Authorized Members (employees)
* Mailbox → has one Mailbox Manager (portal user) and can reference many Authorized Members for USPS compliance


# **2\. Users, roles, and permissions**

All access is tenant-scoped. A user may belong to multiple operators and multiple mailboxes.

## **2.1 Roles**

| Role | Capabilities |
| :---- | :---- |
| Admin Owner | Full access to operator settings, integrations, billing, and all locations. |
| Location Staff | Mail intake, requests processing, mailbox management for assigned locations. |
| Compliance Reviewer | Can view and approve/reject compliance cases and upload/export CMRAs. |
| Billing Admin | Can view invoices, manage payment methods, and configure billing integrations. |
| Mailbox Manager | Customer portal access to a mailbox and can create requests. |
| Read-only Mailbox Manager | Customer portal access but cannot create requests (optional; feature flag). |

## **2.2 Permission rules**

* Admin Tool users must select an operator account at login if they belong to multiple, then select a location context.  
* Location Staff can only see mail, requests, and mailboxes for the locations they are assigned to.  
* Mailbox Managers can only see mail items and requests for mailboxes they are assigned to.  
* Compliance documents and images are sensitive; access is restricted to Admin roles and mailbox managers for their own mailbox.

# **4\. Data model and enums**

This section defines the minimum data required to implement the screens and flows. Table names are suggestions; the implementation may map to existing C3scan tables (operator, location, company, etc.) as long as semantics match.

## **4.1 Core entities**

Core entities (v0.2 minimum)

operator: Top-level tenant entity (coworking operator).

location: Physical site; scopes staff activity and mail storage.

mailbox: Customer mailbox (virtual office), linked to the company and its members.

mail\_item: A scanned/received piece of mail. Stores image storage\_path(s) and extracted metadata.

request: Customer action request for a mail\_item. Types include forward and open\_scan.

request\_attachment: File(s) attached to a request, used primarily for Open & Scan deliverables (PDF/images) and shipping label PDFs for Forward.

request\_note: Freeform notes on a request (staff internal, and optionally customer-visible if flagged).

request\_event: Append-only activity trail for request lifecycle (created, assigned, in\_progress, attachment\_added, note\_added, completed, canceled).

Request attachments/notes/events required fields: request\_id (uuid), created\_at, created\_by (user\_id), and storage\_path for attachments. Notes include note\_body (text) and visibility (staff\_only|customer\_visible). Events include event\_type and optional metadata json.

| Entity | Key fields (minimum) |
| :---- | :---- |
| operator | operator\_id (uuid), operator\_name, is\_active |
| location | location\_id (uuid), operator\_id, location\_name, address fields, is\_active |
| mailbox | mailbox\_id (uuid), operator\_id, location\_id, pmb (text), mailbox\_name, status (active/cancelled), offering\_plan\_id, created\_at |
| user\_account | user\_id (uuid), email, phone, first\_name, last\_name, created\_at, is\_active |
| mailbox\_membership | mailbox\_id, user\_id, role (manager/read\_only), status (active/pending), invited\_at, accepted\_at |
| company | company\_id (uuid), operator\_id, company\_name, status (active/inactive), created\_at |
| company\_alias | company\_alias\_id (uuid), company\_id, alias\_type (e.g., authorized\_member, dba, ocr\_variant), alias\_name, created\_at, is\_active |
| mail\_item | mail\_item\_id, mailbox\_id, location\_id, package\_type, status, uploaded\_at, received\_at, carrier, tracking\_number, created\_by |
| mail\_item\_image | image\_id, mail\_item\_id, image\_type (envelope/label/other), storage\_path, width, height, created\_at |
| mail\_request | request\_id, mail\_item\_id, mailbox\_id, request\_type, request\_status, requested\_by\_user\_id, requested\_at, completed\_at, notes, metadata\_json |
| compliance\_case | mailbox\_id (pk), status, grace\_deadline, last\_reminder\_at, created\_at, updated\_at |
| compliance\_document | document\_id, mailbox\_id, document\_type, storage\_path, extracted\_fields\_json, verified\_by, verified\_at |
| signature | signature\_id, mailbox\_id, signer\_name, signature\_svg\_path or signature\_png\_path, signed\_at |
| integration\_config | operator\_id, integration\_type, config\_json (encrypted at rest where needed), is\_enabled |
| offering\_plan | offering\_plan\_id, operator\_id, name, price\_cents, currency, is\_active |
| billing\_invoice | invoice\_id, operator\_id, mailbox\_id, period\_start, period\_end, amount\_cents, status, due\_date, created\_at, pdf\_path |
| payment\_method | payment\_method\_id, operator\_id, brand, last4, exp\_month, exp\_year, created\_at |

## **4.2 Enumerations**

### **Mail item package\_type**

* correspondence  
* package

### **Mail item status**

| Status | Meaning |
| :---- | :---- |
| uploaded | Intake complete; no customer action yet |
| open\_scan\_requested | Customer requested open and scan; pending processing |
| open\_scan\_completed | Scan complete; customer can view |
| forward\_requested | Forward requested; pending shipping |
| forward\_shipped | Forwarded and shipped |
| pickup\_requested | Onsite pickup requested |
| picked\_up | Picked up and completed |
| shred\_requested | Shred requested |
| recycle\_requested | Recycle requested |
| disposed | Disposed (shred or recycle completed) |
| deposit\_requested | Deposit requested (for checks) |
| deposited | Deposit completed |
| left\_at\_office | Left at office per request or automation |
| archived | Hidden from default inbox view |

### **Request types**

* open\_scan  
* forward  
* pickup  
* shred  
* recycle  
* deposit  
* leave\_at\_office  
* weekly\_forward  
* biweekly\_forward

### **Request status**

* pending  
* in\_progress  
* completed  
* cancelled

### **Compliance status**

| Status | Meaning |
| :---- | :---- |
| pending | Customer has not completed required steps |
| under\_review | Customer submitted; awaiting staff review |
| compliant | Approved and CMRA/1583 recorded |
| non\_compliant | Past grace period; service restrictions may apply |
| rejected | Submitted but rejected; requires resubmission |

## **4.3 Storage and PII rules**

* All images and documents are stored in private object storage. The database stores storage\_path, not a public URL.  
* Clients retrieve images via time-limited signed URLs scoped to the authenticated user and tenant.  
* Do not embed PII in object keys (paths). Use opaque UUID-based paths.  
* All integration secrets (Stripe secret key, OfficeRnD client secret, etc.) must be encrypted at rest and never logged.

# **5\. Admin Tool functional spec**

This section maps directly to the Admin Tool pages visible in screenshots. For each page: components, behavior, validation, and acceptance criteria are specified.

## **5.1 Authentication, account selection, and location context**

### **5.1.1 Login**

UI: email and password login screen.

Acceptance criteria:

* Submitting valid credentials signs the user in and creates a session.  
* Invalid credentials show an inline error and do not disclose whether the email exists.  
* Password field supports show/hide.

### **5.1.2 Select operator account**

UI: 'Find your account' screen listing operator accounts the user can access.

* If the user belongs to exactly one operator, skip this screen.  
* Selecting an operator sets tenant context for the session.

### **5.1.3 Select location**

UI: modal with location cards (e.g., Thinkspace Seattle, Thinkspace Redmond).

* Location selection scopes mail intake, requests processing, and mailbox lists by default.  
* Users with multi-location access may switch locations from a persistent header selector.

## **5.2 Mail list**

UI elements (from screenshots): search by PMB or mailbox, status filter, package type filter, view toggle, Upload Mail button, pagination.

### **5.2.1 Data shown per row**

* mail\_item\_id (display as short ID)  
* pmb  
* mailbox\_name  
* package\_type  
* status  
* uploaded\_date  
* row actions menu (kebab)

### **5.2.2 Filters and search**

* Search matches PMB prefix, mailbox name (contains), and mail item ID.  
* Status filter uses Mail item status enumeration.  
* Package type filter includes at minimum Correspondence and Package.  
* Filters persist in URL query params for sharable links.

### **5.2.3 Upload mail entry points**

* Upload Mail opens the upload flow (see 5.3).  
* After successful upload, return to the mail list with a success toast; ensure new item is visible under current filters.

### **5.2.4 Mail item detail (required)**

Although screenshots focus on list views, v0.2 must include a mail item detail view to support processing. The detail view can be a right-side drawer.

* Show envelope image (and label image if available) via signed URL.  
* Show metadata: mailbox, PMB, package type, carrier, tracking, uploaded date, current status.  
* Show request history timeline for the mail item.  
* Allow staff to add internal notes and to mark a request as completed from this screen.

## **5.3 Upload mail**

Admin upload supports manual entry when mail was not ingested via the iOS app or needs correction.

### **5.3.1 Required fields**

* Mailbox selection (searchable by PMB or name)  
* Package type (Correspondence or Package)  
* At least one image (envelope front)

### **5.3.2 Optional fields**

* Carrier (USPS, UPS, FedEx)  
* Tracking number  
* Received date (defaults to today)  
* Internal notes

### **5.3.3 Validation**

* PMB is stored as text to preserve leading zeros.  
* Reject uploads larger than configured max size per image; show friendly error.  
* If mailbox is cancelled, warn and require confirmation before uploading.

### **5.3.4 Acceptance criteria**

* Creating a mail item uploads images to private storage and creates mail\_item plus mail\_item\_image records.  
* System stores image dimensions; thumbnails are generated.  
* A notification event is emitted for the mailbox managers (in-app; email optional v0.2).

## **5.4 Mailboxes**

UI (from screenshots): list with Active, Cancelled, All tabs; actions for Download CSV, Import, Export, Export CMRAs, New Mailbox; detail panel on selection.

### **5.4.1 Mailbox list columns**

* PMB  
* Name  
* Mailbox Status  
* Compliance  
* Created on

### **5.4.2 Mailbox detail panel**

* Offering Plan (dropdown)  
* Registered company name (text)  
* Phone (text)  
* Address (multi-line)  
* Mailbox Managers list  
* Invite new managers input plus Invite button  
* Pending Invitations list

### **5.4.3 Invitations**

* Inviting a manager creates a mailbox\_membership with status=pending and sends an invitation email containing a single-use token link.  
* Invitation email contains mailbox name and PMB and an Accept Invitation button.  
* Accepting an invitation either logs the user in (existing account) or routes to registration with pre-filled email.  
* Invitations expire after configurable TTL (default 7 days) and can be re-sent.

### **5.4.4 Import and export**

* Download CSV exports the current filtered list.  
* Import accepts CSV with PMB and mailbox name at minimum. Validate duplicates and report row-level errors.  
* Export generates a full mailbox export for backup.  
* Export CMRAs exports compliance PDF packet per mailbox where status=compliant.

### **5.4.5 New mailbox**

* Create mailbox modal requires location, mailbox name, and PMB number.  
* PMB format is governed by Settings: General (sequential or alphanumeric).  
* On create, compliance\_case is created with status=pending and grace\_deadline computed from grace period setting.

## **5.5 Requests**

UI (from screenshots): Request dashboard with count cards per request type and lists for Pending, Completed, All Requests.

### **5.5.1 Request dashboard cards**

Cards: Open and Scan, Shred, Recycle, Forward, Pickup, Deposit, plus Weekly Forward, Biweekly Forward, Leave At Office.

Each card shows a count of pending requests of that type in the selected location context.

### **5.5.2 Request list columns**

* Request Details (type plus request\_id)  
* Mailbox  
* Requested By  
* Date

### **5.5.3 Request detail (required)**

Selecting a request opens a detail view with:

* Mail item images (envelope, label, scanned contents if any)  
* Requested action details, including shipping address for forward or pickup scheduling info  
* Internal processing checklist (varies by type)  
* Buttons: Mark In Progress, Mark Completed, Cancel request (admin)

#### ***Forward Mail \- request detail view (Admin Tool)***

![][image1]

**Reference UI: Admin request detail \- Forward Mail (top).**

![][image2]

**Reference UI: Admin request detail \- Forward Mail (details).**

* Primary action: green 'Forward Mail' button. Secondary controls: close/cancel (X) and next/advance (arrow) to navigate request queue.  
* Read-only identifiers shown near top: request\_id, mailbox name, mail\_item\_id, and a mail image preview component.  
* Forward destination section (required): recipient\_name, address\_line1, optional address\_line2, city, state\_province, postal\_code, country\_code.  
* Carrier/service (required): display selected service (e.g., USPS FirstClass). Admin may override if role \>= location\_manager; overrides create a request\_event.  
* Completion workflow: clicking 'Forward Mail' (a) validates address, (b) creates shipment \+ label (via shipping integration), (c) stores label as request\_attachment, (d) sets request.status=in\_progress then completed (or completed directly if instant), (e) logs request\_event entries for each step.

#### ***Open & Scan \- request detail view (Admin Tool)***

![][image3]

**Reference UI: Admin request detail \- Open & Scan (top).**

![][image4]

**Reference UI: Admin request detail \- Open & Scan (deliverables, notes, activity).**

* Primary action: green 'Mark as Completed' button. Secondary controls: close/cancel (X) and next/advance (arrow).  
* Read-only identifiers shown: request\_id, mailbox name, mail\_item\_id, and a mail image preview component.  
* Deliverables upload (required): 'Upload Files' dropzone with drag-and-drop \+ 'Add a File'. Each uploaded file becomes a request\_attachment and is visible to the customer upon completion.  
* Notes (required): staff can add notes; at minimum staff\_only notes. Optionally support customer\_visible notes for status updates.  
* Activity trail (required): append-only event log showing who requested, timestamps, transitions, and file uploads.

* Completion records outcome metadata (tracking number for forward, pickup confirmation, disposal confirmation, deposit confirmation)

### **5.5.4 Acceptance criteria**

* Completing a request updates mail\_request.status to completed and updates mail\_item.status to a corresponding terminal state (e.g., disposed, forward\_shipped).  
* Customer receives an in-app notification that the request is complete (email optional v0.2).  
* All request updates are auditable (server logs at minimum).

## **5.6 Members**

UI: members list with search; columns include full legal name, role (Mailbox Manager or Authorized Member), portal access (yes or no), and contact fields (email, phone) when available.

* Members are tied to a Company and its Mailbox(es) for operational and USPS compliance reasons, and may include individuals who do not have portal access.
* Mailbox Managers are the portal users who signed the lease and can act in the Customer Tool. A Mailbox Manager can also appear on the Authorized Member roster.
* Authorized Members are the USPS compliance roster for a Company or Mailbox. In v0.2, these are stored in `company_alias` with `alias_type = "authorized_member"` and `alias_name` set to the person’s full legal name.
* Admin can search members by name and filter by role and portal access. Search by email or phone is supported for Mailbox Managers and any Members with contact info on file.
* Clicking a member shows their associated Company, Mailbox(es), and compliance documents (read-only in v0.2).

## **5.7 Compliance**

UI: compliance list with tabs for compliant and non compliant, search, and a detail panel.

### **5.7.1 Compliance list behavior**

* Tabs show counts of compliant and non compliant mailboxes.  
* Non compliant includes pending and rejected and those past grace\_deadline.  
* Selecting a mailbox loads compliance detail.

### **5.7.2 Compliance detail panel**

* Header: PMB and mailbox name, status badge (Pending, Compliant, etc.)  
* Summary metrics: members count, business use indicator, document upload status  
* Alerts for missing fields (e.g., missing place of registration) with action buttons  
* Action: Mark as uploaded (admin override)  
* Action: Manage invitations

### **5.7.3 Reminder emails**

* Frequency options: Never, Weekly, Biweekly, Monthly.  
* Grace period in days controls when a mailbox becomes non compliant.  
* Reminder emails include deep link to customer compliance assistant.

## **5.8 Billing**

UI: payment methods, billing history, invoice list with filters.

### **5.8.1 Payment methods**

* List saved payment methods (brand plus last4 plus exp), with actions menu.  
* Add Payment Method launches Stripe setup flow (Stripe Elements) when Stripe is enabled.  
* Only Billing Admin and Admin Owner can modify payment methods.

### **5.8.2 Billing history and invoices**

* Billing history table shows period, amount, status, and download action (PDF).  
* Invoice list supports filtering by period and searching by invoice ID.  
* Invoices are tied to operator and mailbox; staff can open mailbox from invoice row.

## **5.9 Settings**

Settings are operator-scoped unless explicitly location-scoped.

### **5.9.1 General**

* Support Email, Support Phone  
* PMB format: Sequential or Alphanumeric  
* Scheduled Pickup Hours per weekday (enabled toggle plus start/end time)

### **5.9.2 Offerings**

* Currency (e.g., US Dollar)  
* Offering self-serve link toggle  
* Mailbox Offering Plans list with add plan action  
* Plan card shows name, price, and view details icon

### **5.9.3 Carriers**

* Checkbox toggles for USPS, UPS, FedEx.  
* Apply Changes persists carrier availability and updates carrier dropdown options elsewhere.

### **5.9.4 Banks**

* Bank institutions list (for deposit requests).  
* Add bank institution modal: name, plus optional routing details and instructions.  
* Apply Changes persists list.

### **5.9.5 Brand**

* Brand color picker.  
* Brand logo upload.  
* Portal preview updates in real time.

### **5.9.6 Compliance**

* Compliance enabled toggle.  
* Follow-up email frequency: Never, Weekly, Biweekly, Monthly.  
* Grace period in days.  
* Agent signature: capture and store signature (canvas) and allow edit.

### **5.9.7 Access**

* Operator Access list of staff users.  
* Invite staff by email; creates staff invitation flow.  
* Invited staff must accept invite and set password.

### **5.9.8 Automations**

* Toggles: Auto Open and Scan, Auto Leave at Office, Auto Recurrent Forward.  
* Frequency selector for recurrent forward: Weekly, Biweekly, Monthly.  
* Apply Changes persists operator defaults. Mailbox overrides are optional in v0.2.

### **5.9.9 Integrations**

Cards: Stripe, EasyPost, OfficeRnD, Deskworks. Each opens a modal matching screenshots.

* Stripe: Account ID, Public Key, Secret Key, toggle 'Bill mailbox members with Stripe'.  
* EasyPost: API Key.  
* OfficeRnD: Organization, Client ID, Client Secret, Signing Secret, toggle billing, Copy Webhook Endpoint URL, mapping sections (Plans to Mailbox Offerings, Locations to Spaces).  
* Deskworks: Username, Password, Tenant URL, toggle billing, Select Mail Services Product, mapping section (Plans to Mailbox Offerings).

# **6\. Customer Tool functional spec**

This section maps to the mailbox manager portal screenshots and fills in required behaviors for a usable product.

## **6.1 Invitation and onboarding**

### **6.1.1 Invitation email**

* Email subject: New Invitation.  
* Body includes mailbox name and PMB, and an Accept Invitation button.  
* Accept link format: /app/invite/:token where token is single-use and scoped to mailbox\_membership.

### **6.1.2 Account creation**

UI: Welcome to your new mailbox form with Email (pre-filled), Phone number, First name, Last name, Password, Create Account.

* Email is locked when arriving from an invitation token.  
* Password requirements: minimum 10 chars, at least one letter and one number (configurable).  
* On successful create, send email confirmation.

### **6.1.3 Email confirmation**

* Confirmation email contains a Confirm Your Email button linking to /app/confirm-email/:token.  
* After confirmation, route user to mailbox selection (if multiple) or inbox.

### **6.1.4 Mailbox selection**

UI: Choose your mailbox with buttons/cards for each mailbox user manages.

* Selecting a mailbox sets active mailbox context and routes to /app/:mailbox\_id/mail.  
* User can switch mailboxes from a header dropdown.

## **6.2 Inbox**

### **6.2.1 Layout and controls**

* Header: mailbox selector, nav tabs Mail and Compliance, notification icon, user menu.  
* Banner appears when compliance not complete with Finish compliance button.  
* Controls: View Archived toggle, Filter by status dropdown.

### **6.2.2 Empty state**

Empty inbox shows illustration and text 'No snail mail found.'

### **6.2.3 Status filter**

Dropdown options (from screenshot): Uploaded, Open and Scan, Shred, Recycle, Forward, Pickup, Deposited, Left At Office.

### **6.2.4 Mail item list (required)**

Mail items render as cards or rows with thumbnail, uploaded date, and status. Clicking opens mail item detail.

## **6.3 Mail item detail and customer requests (required)**

PilotoMail screenshots do not include this view, but it is required for v0.2.

### **6.3.1 Detail view components**

* Envelope images and label image (if package).  
* Metadata: received date, location, carrier, tracking, status.  
* Action buttons: Open and Scan, Forward, Pickup, Shred, Recycle, Deposit, Leave at office.  
* Request history timeline.

### **6.3.2 Request creation common rules**

* Creating a request shows a confirmation modal (fees displayed if applicable).  
* Only one active request per mail item at a time (server enforced).  
* Customer cancellation allowed while request\_status=pending (optional v0.2).

### **6.3.3 Forward request**

* Collect shipping address.  
* Optional shipping speed if supported.  
* On submit, create mail\_request and set mail\_item.status=forward\_requested.

Customer view after submitting a Forward request

* Immediately after submit: show success toast/inline confirmation; set mail item 'has\_active\_request' and display request status chip (Pending/In progress/Completed).  
* Customer can open a request summary panel from the mail item detail showing: destination recipient \+ address, chosen carrier/service, and request\_id.  
* When completed: show tracking number \+ carrier label download (signed URL) and completion timestamp.

### **6.3.4 Pickup request**

* Show pickup window based on scheduled pickup hours.  
* Collect optional note and pickup person name.

### **6.3.5 Open and scan request**

* Confirm user authorizes opening mail.  
* After completion, scanned images appear in detail view and status becomes open\_scan\_completed.

Customer view after submitting an Open & Scan request

* Immediately after submit: show confirmation; status chip set to Pending. Customer sees estimated processing time (configurable per location).  
* In mail item detail, customer sees request summary (request\_id, requested\_at, current status).  
* When staff uploads deliverables and marks completed: customer sees attached files list (request\_attachments) with signed download links; optional customer-visible note appears as a status update.

### **6.3.6 Shred and recycle requests**

* Confirm irreversible action.  
* After completion, mail\_item.status becomes disposed.

### **6.3.7 Deposit request**

* Collect deposit instructions and optionally bank selection.  
* Admin completion attaches receipt metadata.

### **6.3.8 Leave at office and recurring forward**

* Leave at office collects instructions; processing sets mail\_item.status=left\_at\_office.  
* Weekly and biweekly forward create a recurring schedule for the mailbox (admin-visible).

* Admin may reject with reason; customer sees status and can resubmit.  
* On approval, status becomes compliant, banner disappears, and case is included in Export CMRAs.

* Attach label PDF to request and allow admin download.

## **8.2 Stripe**

* Used for operator billing configuration and payment method storage.  
* Support Stripe customer per mailbox (or per manager, configurable).  
* Webhooks update billing\_invoice status (paid, failed, open).

## **8.3 OfficeRnD and Deskworks**

* Sync members, plans, and spaces. Supports billing mailbox members from the source system.  
* Webhook endpoint verifies signing secret.  
* Maintain mapping tables for external plan ids and location ids.

## **8.4 Scheduled jobs**

* Compliance reminder sender runs daily; sends reminders per frequency to mailboxes not compliant.  
* Grace period enforcer runs daily; sets status to non\_compliant when grace\_deadline passed.  
* Recurring forward generator runs daily; creates forward requests per mailbox schedule.

# **9\. Security, privacy, and RLS requirements**

* Row-level security: enforce operator\_id and mailbox\_id membership on all reads and writes.  
* Storage security: only signed URLs; never public buckets for mail images or compliance documents.  
* PII minimization: do not log addresses, ID numbers, or document URLs; log only record IDs.  
* Admin override actions require elevated role and must be recorded in an audit trail table.

## **9.1 Session management**

* Idle timeout configurable (default 12 hours).  
* Re-authenticate or require elevated confirmation before displaying integration secrets.

## 12. Geofencing Feature (Mobile App)

### 12.1 Overview
This feature enables the c3scan iOS app to determine a user's current coworking location and operator based on their phone's latitude and longitude. It supports multiple operators and includes a customizable geofence radius setting.

### 12.2 Security Model (CRITICAL)

**Operator Domain Isolation:**
- The operator_id is determined at login based on the user's email domain
- The JWT token contains the operator_id and is cryptographically signed
- The geofence API uses the operator_id from the JWT token to filter locations
- **A Thinkspace employee can NEVER see 25N locations, even if physically standing next to one**

**Security Boundaries:**
1. **Authentication Layer**: JWT token validates user identity
2. **Authorization Layer**: operator_id in token restricts data to user's operator only
3. **Client Verification**: iOS app verifies operator_id in response matches current user
4. **Audit Logging**: All geofence detections are logged with user_id, operator_id, and coordinates

### 12.3 Technical Flow (API-Based)

1. **Latitude/Longitude Read**: On user login or when "Detect Location" is tapped, the app retrieves the device's current GPS coordinates using iOS CoreLocation.

2. **API Geofence Detection**: The app sends GPS coordinates to the backend API `POST /api/mobile/v1/geofence/detect` with the configured radius (default 10 miles).

3. **Server-Side Distance Calculation**: The API uses the Haversine formula to calculate distance between user's GPS coordinates and all operator locations stored in the database.

4. **Operator Filtering**: API filters locations by operator_id from JWT token, ensuring cross-operator isolation.

5. **Client Verification**: iOS app verifies the operator_id in the response matches the logged-in user's operator.

6. **Multiple Locations Handling**: 
   - If **one location** is found within radius → Auto-select it
   - If **multiple locations** are found → Show location picker to employee
   - If **no locations** found → Prompt to select manually or increase radius

7. **Context Setting**: Selected location ID is saved to UserDefaults and used for all subsequent API calls (sync, upload, etc.).

### 12.3 Geofencing API

**Endpoint**: `POST /api/mobile/v1/geofence/detect`

**Request Body**:
```json
{
  "latitude": 47.6062,
  "longitude": -122.3321,
  "radius_miles": 10.0
}
```

**Response Body**:
```json
{
  "user_location": {
    "latitude": 47.6062,
    "longitude": -122.3321
  },
  "radius_miles": 10.0,
  "locations": [
    {
      "location_id": "db4aaf76-426c-4b2b-bbb2-c7e4b9b687bf",
      "location_name": "Thinkspace Redmond",
      "address": {
        "street": "16150 NE 85th St",
        "city": "Redmond",
        "state": "WA",
        "zip": "98052"
      },
      "latitude": 47.6784,
      "longitude": -122.1234,
      "distance_miles": 6.2
    }
  ],
  "count": 1,
  "operator_id": "db4aaf76-426c-4b2b-bbb2-c7e4b9b687bf",
  "closest_location": {
    "location_id": "db4aaf76-426c-4b2b-bbb2-c7e4b9b687bf",
    "location_name": "Thinkspace Redmond",
    "distance_miles": 6.2
  }
}
```

**Security Notes:**
- `operator_id` in response is returned for client-side verification
- API only returns locations for the operator_id extracted from the JWT token
- Cross-operator location leakage is prevented at the database query level

### 12.4 Data Tables

**Operator Table**: Contains details for all operators (e.g., Thinkspace, 25N, Blankspaces).
- `operator_id` (UUID)
- `operator_name` (text)
- `email_domain` (text) - Used for mobile auth operator resolution
- `is_active` (boolean)
- `created_at`, `updated_at` (timestamps)

**Location Table**: Lists each physical location with geofence coordinates and linked operator IDs.
- `location_id` (UUID)
- `operator_id` (UUID) - FK to operator
- `location_name` (text)
- `address_line1`, `address_line2`, `city`, `state_province`, `postal_code`, `country_code` (text)
- `latitude` (decimal) - GPS latitude for geofencing
- `longitude` (decimal) - GPS longitude for geofencing
- `geofence_radius_meters` (integer) - Default radius, overridable in app settings
- `is_active` (boolean)
- `created_at`, `updated_at` (timestamps)

### 12.5 Mobile App Authentication Flow

**App Launch Sequence (StartupPipeline):**

1. **App Start** → Database initialization → Camera initialization
2. **Check Google OAuth Status**:
   - If NOT authenticated → Show Login screen immediately
   - If ALREADY authenticated → Proceed to permission check
3. **Permission Check** (Camera & Location):
   - **Camera**: Already requested during CameraView initialization
   - **Location**: StartupPipeline requests `NSLocationWhenInUseUsageDescription`
   - iOS system dialog appears on first launch: "Location access is used to automatically detect your coworking site when you log in."
   - Pipeline waits for user response (up to 30 seconds)
   - If denied, app continues without geolocation (user can manually select location)
4. **Geolocation Check** (runs on EVERY login/app launch if authenticated and permitted):
   - Get current GPS coordinates
   - Call `POST /api/mobile/v1/geofence/detect`
   - Auto-select closest location within radius
   - Show location picker if multiple locations found
5. **Cache Sync**: Sync company aliases for offline matching
6. **Main Camera Screen** appears (ready for scanning)

**StartupPipeline Features:**
- **Guaranteed execution**: All critical tasks run in sequence
- **Permission handling**: Gracefully handles camera/location permission dialogs
- **Error resilience**: Continues even if geolocation or cache sync fails
- **Progress tracking**: UI can show startup progress
- **Re-runnable**: Can be reset and re-run after logout

**Logout Flow:**
1. User taps **Log Out** in Settings
2. Auth token is cleared immediately
3. **Login screen appears automatically** (no manual steps)
4. User must sign in with Google to continue
5. After successful login → **StartupPipeline runs again** → Location updated

**Key Principles:**
- **No "remember me" that bypasses login** - User must authenticate every session
- **Geolocation on every login** - Location is always checked after authentication (if permitted)
- **Forced re-authentication** - Logout immediately triggers login screen
- **Permission-first**: System permissions requested at appropriate times

### 12.6 Mobile App Settings

**Settings Screen Layout (Top to Bottom)**:

1. **Account Information Section** (Top of screen, always visible when authenticated)
   - **Operator Name** (with building.2 icon, blue)
   - **Employee Email** (with envelope icon, green) 
   - **Current Location** (with mappin.and.ellipse icon, orange)
   - **Log Out** button (red, centered) - logs out and returns to login
   - *Purpose: Always-visible context for which operator/location the employee is working under*

2. **Location Settings Section** (only when authenticated)
   - Location picker (if multiple locations available)
   - Current location display (if single location)
   - Loading indicator during location fetch

3. **Geofencing Section**
   - Detection Radius picker
   - "Detect Location Automatically" button
   - Options: 100m, 500m, 1mi, 3mi, 6mi, 10mi, 20mi
   - Default: 10 miles
   - Storage: Saved locally in UserDefaults

4. **Photo Storage Section**
   - Toggle: Save to c3scan.io Album
   - Toggle: Keep Separate from Camera Roll (when enabled)

5. **About Section**
   - App Version
   - Build Number

**Settings Screen Flow:**
- User opens Settings
- If authenticated: Shows Operator, Email, Location, Logout button
- If NOT authenticated: Shows "Not Signed In" prompt with Sign In button
- **Tapping Logout**: Clears auth token → **Immediately shows login screen** → User must re-authenticate

**Security Context Display**:
The Account Information section at the top serves as a persistent security indicator, ensuring the employee always knows:
- Which operator they are representing
- Which email account they're logged in as
- Which location their scans will be assigned to

### 12.7 Expected Outcome

When a user logs in, the app will accurately set the session for the correct operator and location, with the flexibility of adjusting the geofence radius to suit different scenarios. This ensures that even during testing or special cases, the correct location context is applied.

### 12.7 Privacy Considerations

- GPS location is only read at login and when manually refreshing location
- Location data is not stored on the server, only used for session context
- Users can disable geofencing and manually select location
- All location processing happens on-device
